of what drives me
forward in fusion.

01:32.693 --> 01:36.306
Imagine you're reaching up
and you're grabbing the sun,

01:36.330 --> 01:39.309
something of the order of a
100 million degrees Celsius,

01:39.333 --> 01:41.469
and you want to put
the sun in a bottle.

01:48.642 --> 01:52.822
And we have ways of doing that.
We create a magnetic model.

01:52.846 --> 01:56.193
Compared to anything that mankind
has ever done in the past,

01:56.217 --> 01:59.929
be it walking on the moon,
be it decoding DNA,

01:59.953 --> 02:01.522
this is a great challenge.

02:03.391 --> 02:06.470
We, as humans, we're lazy.

02:06.494 --> 02:09.306
In the sense that if we
have a choice of going

02:09.330 --> 02:11.808
a very easy path or
very complicated path,

02:11.832 --> 02:13.343
we would always
go the easy path.

02:13.367 --> 02:14.911
And that's what we're
doing with energy.

02:14.935 --> 02:17.181
We're burning fossil fuels,

02:17.205 --> 02:19.516
coal, natural gas, crude oil,

02:19.540 --> 02:21.642
and that is changing
the environment.

02:32.420 --> 02:35.332
We're similar to, I hate
to say it, to yeast,

02:35.356 --> 02:37.534
where the yeast basically
multiply, multiply, multiply,

02:37.558 --> 02:40.537
eat up all of the
flour and the dough

02:40.561 --> 02:43.840
until basically they die off
from their own excrement,

02:43.864 --> 02:45.942
uh, because they've just eaten
up all their resources,

02:45.966 --> 02:48.602
and they've died from their own
pollution that they've created.

03:05.719 --> 03:07.597
We have to find a clean source

03:07.621 --> 03:09.799
that's going to be
available for lifetimes,

03:09.823 --> 03:12.436
and that's what fusion is.

03:12.460 --> 03:15.004
I really feel that if we don't
crack fusion, we are doomed,

03:15.028 --> 03:16.597
to be honest.

04:44.852 --> 04:46.763
What we're trying to
do here is to make

04:46.787 --> 04:48.565
a artificial star.

04:48.589 --> 04:51.067
Stars have some things
we don't have on Earth,

04:51.091 --> 04:52.793
size and mass.

04:53.961 --> 04:57.341
The Sun, for example, is a
very nice fusion reactor

04:57.365 --> 04:59.509
that enjoys considerable
public support,

04:59.533 --> 05:01.611
and it works on the
basis of gravity

05:01.635 --> 05:04.948
plus its magnetic field,
uh, to confine the plasma.

05:04.972 --> 05:07.617
Now, the sun is really big,

05:07.641 --> 05:10.019
800,000 miles, something
like, across.

05:10.043 --> 05:12.789
Uh, we clearly don't
want anything that big,

05:12.813 --> 05:15.616
so we have to rely on the
magnetic fields alone.

05:18.819 --> 05:20.964
That turns out to be doable,

05:20.988 --> 05:23.800
but technologically difficult
to do on a large scale.

05:23.824 --> 05:25.769
And so we've been
learning how to do this

05:25.793 --> 05:27.595
for about 40 or 50 years.

05:33.601 --> 05:37.080
What's amazing about work in
that era is we didn't know

05:37.104 --> 05:40.884
what the energy process
that drove stars was.

05:53.487 --> 05:56.132
Hans Bethe, the
nuclear physicist,

05:56.156 --> 05:57.734
uh, was at a seminar,

05:57.758 --> 06:00.504
and the next day he
was gonna give a talk

06:00.528 --> 06:03.807
where he talked about a fusion
fuel cycle for the stars.

06:03.831 --> 06:07.911
But he had a date that night, and
so they went out for a walk.

06:07.935 --> 06:11.515
And he came out with what has
to be the best line ever,

06:11.539 --> 06:13.883
which is, "Aren't the
starts beautiful tonight?

06:13.907 --> 06:16.844
And right now, I'm the only guy
in the world who knows why."

06:19.079 --> 06:20.156
In the sun's core,

06:20.180 --> 06:24.428
when these particles are
accelerated to high speeds

06:24.452 --> 06:25.729
and collide...

06:25.753 --> 06:27.421
they fuse.

06:33.661 --> 06:36.573
Fusion fuel is in,
essentially, infinite supply

06:36.597 --> 06:39.533
and is available to all
countries at negligible cost.

06:40.801 --> 06:45.815
The fuel, or fusion...
is in common water.

06:45.839 --> 06:49.553
Fusion will produce no noxious
chemical combustion products,

06:49.577 --> 06:53.523
and there will be absolutely no
chance of a runaway reaction.

06:53.547 --> 06:55.559
And fusion will not
involve materials

06:55.583 --> 06:58.662
that could be stolen or used
for clandestine purposes.

06:58.686 --> 07:01.731
When I came into this project
almost 20 years ago,

07:01.755 --> 07:04.534
there was a tremendous
amount of enthusiasm.

07:04.558 --> 07:06.894
Everyone was confident
of success.

07:10.197 --> 07:12.075
In the Zeta apparatus,

07:12.099 --> 07:14.177
we have produced temperatures

07:14.201 --> 07:16.045
which are about
one-third of those

07:16.069 --> 07:18.047
at the center of the sun.

07:18.071 --> 07:19.583
But this enthusiasm

07:19.607 --> 07:22.018
was a kind of
ignorant enthusiasm.

07:22.042 --> 07:25.054
As fusion researchers have
painfully discovered,

07:25.078 --> 07:26.723
it's just not that simple.

07:26.747 --> 07:28.592
After this initial enthusiasm,

07:28.616 --> 07:31.728
then came a decade of
caution and skepticism.

07:31.752 --> 07:35.231
And now, after 20 years,
we're back to enthusiasm.

07:35.255 --> 07:37.601
In the early 1980s,
we expect to create

07:37.625 --> 07:38.802
many thermal megawatts

07:38.826 --> 07:40.861
of fusion energy for
the first time.

07:56.243 --> 07:58.922
So the whole planet
needs a lot of energy.

07:58.946 --> 08:02.892
And so far, we've been running
mostly on fossil fuels.

08:02.916 --> 08:03.927
Been a good run.

08:03.951 --> 08:06.720
It got us to where we
are, but we have to stop.

08:08.021 --> 08:10.233
So we are trying different
types of energy now,

08:10.257 --> 08:11.267
alternative energy.

08:11.291 --> 08:14.003
But it proved quite
difficult to find something

08:14.027 --> 08:17.006
that's as convenient
and as cost-effective

08:17.030 --> 08:20.076
as oil, gas, and coal.

08:20.100 --> 08:24.581
Now, we know of two way of
making, er, nuclear energy:

08:24.605 --> 08:26.916
Fission and fusion.

08:26.940 --> 08:28.985
Now, in fission, you
take a big nucleus,

08:29.009 --> 08:32.020
you break it in part, in two,
and it makes lots of energy.

08:32.044 --> 08:34.924
This is how the nuclear
reactor today works.

08:34.948 --> 08:36.225
Works pretty good.

08:36.249 --> 08:37.927
And then there is fusion.

08:37.951 --> 08:40.730
Now, I like fusion.
Fusion's much better.

08:40.754 --> 08:43.600
So you take two small
nucleus, you put it together,

08:43.624 --> 08:44.834
and you make helium.

08:44.858 --> 08:47.170
And that's very nice.
Makes lots of energy.

08:47.194 --> 08:50.807
And if the whole planet would
run on fusion, it would run...

08:50.831 --> 08:52.576
We could extract the
fuel from the ocean,

08:52.600 --> 08:55.745
it would run for billions
and billions of years.

08:55.769 --> 08:59.182
Now, if fusion is so great,
why don't we have it.

08:59.206 --> 09:00.717
Where is it?

09:00.741 --> 09:02.318
Well, there's always
a bit of a catch.

09:02.342 --> 09:05.054
Fusion is really,
really hard to do.

09:05.078 --> 09:08.925
Physics-wise, fusion is
the, the fusion, ha-ha,

09:08.949 --> 09:09.726
of two nucleus.

09:09.750 --> 09:12.195
Usually, you use a
hydrogen nucleus

09:12.219 --> 09:13.797
or isotope of hydrogen.

09:13.821 --> 09:16.265
And when they touch each
other, they fuse together,

09:16.289 --> 09:17.500
and they make helium

09:17.524 --> 09:20.604
and release a lot of energy in
the form of a fast neutron.

09:20.628 --> 09:23.339
So this is the, the nuclear
reaction in the center.

09:23.363 --> 09:24.473
Now the problem is
those two nucleus,

09:24.497 --> 09:26.810
they're electrically charged,
they're both positive,

09:26.834 --> 09:28.311
so they don't want
to stick together.

09:28.335 --> 09:30.013
They go like this, whoo, shoo,

09:30.037 --> 09:31.280
and they never fuse.

09:31.304 --> 09:33.717
So in order to fuse, you have
to throw them at great speed.

09:33.741 --> 09:35.952
And speed in a gas
is the temperature.

09:35.976 --> 09:38.387
So you have to heat the gas
so the thermal agitation

09:38.411 --> 09:41.691
is fast enough so the nucleus
can touch each other.

09:41.715 --> 09:44.027
And that temperature is a
150 million degrees C.

09:44.051 --> 09:46.796
That's pretty hot. And this
is how the stars work.

09:46.820 --> 09:48.164
The-The stars are very hot

09:48.188 --> 09:51.067
and inside the star, there
is this fusion reaction.

09:51.091 --> 09:53.803
So on the Earth here,
we need to heat the gas

09:53.827 --> 09:55.304
to 150 million degrees C.

09:55.328 --> 09:59.108
And the other problem is a gas
that hot wants to cool down.

09:59.132 --> 10:00.744
So it cools down really quickly.

10:00.768 --> 10:03.379
So you put some energy
in there to heat it up,

10:03.403 --> 10:04.447
and then the heat escape.

10:04.471 --> 10:06.850
And when it's hot enough,
it makes some reaction,

10:06.874 --> 10:08.918
it makes some fusion,
it makes some energy.

10:08.942 --> 10:10.687
So the name of the
game is to try to get

10:10.711 --> 10:12.112
more energy out than you put in.

11:16.944 --> 11:18.788
The world's most
ambitious attempt

11:18.812 --> 11:21.090
to harvest fusion as
a source of power

11:21.114 --> 11:22.826
is taking shape in France.

11:22.850 --> 11:26.262
The project is costing
13 billion pounds

11:26.286 --> 11:29.198
and it's being backed by a
whole swathe of countries

11:29.222 --> 11:30.958
around the world.

11:52.045 --> 11:54.457
ITER's going to be built
from about a million pieces,

11:54.481 --> 11:55.892
so it's a real nightmare

11:55.916 --> 11:57.927
to know where pieces are
and don't lose them,

11:57.951 --> 11:59.495
know which piece goes where,

11:59.519 --> 12:01.721
wh-what is this piece
that I'm looking at.

12:02.823 --> 12:04.834
We build the tokamak
from the bottom up,

12:04.858 --> 12:06.469
so you can only build
it in a certain way.

12:06.493 --> 12:07.837
So if a certain
piece is missing,

12:07.861 --> 12:09.238
we'll have to wait for it.

12:09.262 --> 12:11.540
So it's key... At the
moment, what we're doing

12:11.564 --> 12:14.243
is a very large planning
effort with all the members

12:14.267 --> 12:17.046
to make sure that each
piece is delivered to us

12:17.070 --> 12:18.581
in good time and
at the right time.

12:18.605 --> 12:21.550
The parties all want to
learn all the technologies,

12:21.574 --> 12:24.387
which means you not giving
one component to a party,

12:24.411 --> 12:26.990
you're giving a piece of a
component, and the other party

12:27.014 --> 12:28.858
wants another piece
of the same component

12:28.882 --> 12:30.526
so that they all can
learn the technology.

12:30.550 --> 12:32.996
It is luckily not so that
we have seven pieces

12:33.020 --> 12:35.564
- of each component that it
will be too difficult...

12:35.588 --> 12:37.433
but we have sometimes
three or four pieces

12:37.457 --> 12:38.902
of each component,
and that means...

12:38.926 --> 12:41.337
We have to talk to our
partners, to the members,

12:41.361 --> 12:42.471
in all the... as you say,

12:42.495 --> 12:43.973
in all these countries
around the world,

12:43.997 --> 12:47.410
in Korea, in Japan, in
Russia, China, US, India.

12:47.434 --> 12:50.579
You have not one
guy to deal with.

12:50.603 --> 12:52.415
You have three or four
guys to deal with

12:52.439 --> 12:53.883
for the same component.

12:53.907 --> 12:55.919
We are pushing the
edge of technology

12:55.943 --> 12:58.888
and therefore, sometimes
we run into problems

12:58.912 --> 13:00.890
and we have to solve
these problems.

13:00.914 --> 13:04.928
Critics point out that the costs
have trebled in five years.

13:04.952 --> 13:07.163
They say the whole
project is a gamble

13:07.187 --> 13:08.397
that won't pay off.

13:08.421 --> 13:11.835
Will we be able, with
our complex structure,

13:11.859 --> 13:14.503
and the money we
have, to be in time?

13:14.527 --> 13:18.207
This is actually the most, uh,
difficult thing at the moment,

13:18.231 --> 13:19.366
to stay in time.

13:20.934 --> 13:22.545
What's slowly taking shape here

13:22.569 --> 13:24.247
in the southern
French countryside

13:24.271 --> 13:28.117
could provide the answer to
the world's energy crisis,

13:28.141 --> 13:31.220
or it might prove one of the
most expensive failures

13:31.244 --> 13:33.013
in scientific history.

