Back when I started in fusion,

14:54.161 --> 14:58.107
back in the 19... mid-1980s,

14:58.131 --> 15:01.144
the idea was that fusion
was gonna be successful,

15:01.168 --> 15:04.413
and we would have
fusion on the grid

15:04.437 --> 15:06.649
in about 50 years.

15:06.673 --> 15:10.419
And now, it's, uh,
35 years into my...

15:10.443 --> 15:12.279
30 years into my career now.

15:13.180 --> 15:16.125
Up until about 2000,
the year 2000,

15:16.149 --> 15:18.094
we were just advancing
and advancing

15:18.118 --> 15:19.953
at really a fast rate.

15:20.687 --> 15:24.600
And now, the problem
is is that, uh,

15:24.624 --> 15:26.602
in order to make the next step,

15:26.626 --> 15:28.504
we just need to go
to a bigger machine

15:28.528 --> 15:30.406
and unfortunately,
bigger machines

15:30.430 --> 15:34.077
take longer to build,
are much more complex.

15:34.101 --> 15:39.215
I know that I will be retiring
before ITER's successful,

15:39.239 --> 15:42.385
so I'm like the guy
building a cathedral,

15:42.409 --> 15:45.588
who have... knows that he's
gonna be putting this brick on,

15:45.612 --> 15:46.755
this brick on, and
this brick on,

15:46.779 --> 15:48.457
and he's gonna be
spending his whole career

15:48.481 --> 15:49.558
putting bricks together,

15:49.582 --> 15:51.427
but he'll never see the
end piece, the cathedral,

15:51.451 --> 15:53.353
that will take hundreds
of years to build.

