and so, in fact
it's the taxpayer

25:22.755 --> 25:24.266
who pays for what we do, right?

25:24.290 --> 25:27.069
So this is not a
private organization

25:27.093 --> 25:28.303
or a private enterprise.

25:28.327 --> 25:31.574
This is one of our
top benchmarks,

25:31.598 --> 25:33.776
that we develop this project

25:33.800 --> 25:37.846
and this fusion reactor for
the benefit of everything.

25:37.870 --> 25:41.183
And we want everybody
to share and to join in

25:41.207 --> 25:43.318
and to be proud of this, right?

25:43.342 --> 25:49.725
So transparency and having
an open-door policy

25:49.749 --> 25:53.119
is one of our top priorities
in ITER communications.

25:55.187 --> 25:57.633
A lot of people talk
about a magnetic model,

25:57.657 --> 25:59.735
and I don't feel there's
a good understanding

25:59.759 --> 26:01.804
of how the magnetic field ties

26:01.828 --> 26:04.039
-with this idea of trapping a particle.
-Mm-hmm.

26:04.063 --> 26:06.041
And then I want to go into
the challenge of ITER.

26:06.065 --> 26:09.077
The question is, well, how
come we're taking a long time?

26:09.101 --> 26:10.879
They made a study back in 1976

26:10.903 --> 26:13.749
that showed that depending
upon how you fund fusion,

26:13.773 --> 26:16.384
you can either get
a fusion device

26:16.408 --> 26:19.187
generating electricity
somewhere in the 1990s

26:19.211 --> 26:22.991
out to 2006 all depending upon
how much money you put in

26:23.015 --> 26:24.660
as a functional time.

26:24.684 --> 26:26.629
And then I'm going
to overlay this

26:26.653 --> 26:29.264
as what the US has
actually been funding.

26:29.288 --> 26:30.699
And the funding has gone up.

26:30.723 --> 26:32.868
It peaked around 1978

26:32.892 --> 26:36.963
and then has dropped well below,
based on today's dollars.

26:37.964 --> 26:39.174
It's very understandable,
very honest,

26:39.198 --> 26:42.978
but I won't do this because we
have the US here on Monday,

26:43.002 --> 26:44.980
uh, physically, and...

26:45.004 --> 26:46.048
it's a very touchy
thing in the US.

26:46.072 --> 26:49.251
Because here you're picking
out the US from the...

26:49.275 --> 26:50.318
We have to be careful we don't,

26:50.342 --> 26:53.388
in official presentation,
want to criticize, right?

26:53.412 --> 26:56.825
We can say it's difficult.
Right?

26:56.849 --> 27:00.328
Because, um, in the 70s,
the funding was wow.

27:00.352 --> 27:02.731
Everybody wanted
fusion to happen now.

27:02.755 --> 27:05.000
-Then everything dropped again.
Right? -Poof! Yeah.

27:05.024 --> 27:07.369
We survived. We managed to
survive, and we're here now

27:07.393 --> 27:10.038
building the world's
largest fusion device.

27:10.062 --> 27:12.775
But it's hard, and
it only happens,

27:12.799 --> 27:16.278
and we say we can deliver, uh,

27:16.302 --> 27:18.847
around the mid of the century...

27:18.871 --> 27:21.884
provided that we have
somebody sort of...

27:21.908 --> 27:24.228
-Funding us in the back.
- funding us in the back. Right?

27:48.134 --> 27:51.113
And so to me, before
we basically die

27:51.137 --> 27:53.982
in our excrement like
yeast molecules,

27:54.006 --> 27:57.085
we need to realize that we
need another energy source.

27:57.109 --> 27:59.454
We need to be... It may not
be for our generation.

27:59.478 --> 28:01.924
I mean, the good news
is we're, we're okay.

28:01.948 --> 28:04.392
But it's the next generation
or the generation after that

28:04.416 --> 28:05.527
or the generation after that.

28:05.551 --> 28:08.463
Yeah, I'm actually surprised
how low the funding is.

28:08.487 --> 28:11.800
Would you be able to have, er...

28:11.824 --> 28:15.738
better progress, faster progress
if you had better funding?

28:15.762 --> 28:17.806
I think so. There was a study
made in one country...

28:17.830 --> 28:19.407
I'm not gonna name
the country...

28:19.431 --> 28:20.909
Back in the 70s.

28:20.933 --> 28:24.747
And they said if you keep
the level of the order

28:24.771 --> 28:26.348
of, let's say, I
think it was about

28:26.372 --> 28:29.017
800 million euros per year,

28:29.041 --> 28:33.188
you would be able to achieve
an ITER-like machine,

28:33.212 --> 28:35.223
uh, within about 20 years.

28:35.247 --> 28:37.893
Then if you drop it down
to about 500 million,

28:37.917 --> 28:40.495
it would be extended
out to about 30 years.

28:40.519 --> 28:42.497
And there is a point
of no return,

28:42.521 --> 28:46.201
where basically if you
invested 300 million euros

28:46.225 --> 28:47.169
on a year-to-year basis,

28:47.193 --> 28:50.105
you would actually...
It would take infinity

28:50.129 --> 28:51.406
to achieve a reactor.

28:51.430 --> 28:55.143
Because there you had to keep
the supporting technology base,

28:55.167 --> 28:57.179
the administrative funds.

28:57.203 --> 29:01.149
If you go below 300 million,
you'll never get fusion.

29:01.173 --> 29:02.517
Well...

29:02.541 --> 29:04.052
that country has never invested

29:04.076 --> 29:06.088
more than something
like 200 million euros.

29:06.112 --> 29:09.024
The more money you put into
it, the faster the return.

29:09.048 --> 29:11.559
And-And we really have
been putting in peanuts.

29:11.583 --> 29:15.931
I don't think there's a
broad public acceptance

29:15.955 --> 29:19.567
of hydrogen fusion in the
United States at this stage.

29:19.591 --> 29:24.339
Uh, people back in the
US still in general

29:24.363 --> 29:25.874
don't understand the differences

29:25.898 --> 29:28.410
between uranium fission,

29:28.434 --> 29:32.347
which is the process that's been
used in nuclear power plants

29:32.371 --> 29:34.249
for over 40 years now,

29:34.273 --> 29:36.284
and hydrogen fusion,

29:36.308 --> 29:39.321
uh, which is believe is the
process of the future.

29:39.345 --> 29:43.025
You have to keep in mind a
couple of things, you know.

29:43.049 --> 29:46.561
First, this is one of the grand
challenges of engineering.

29:46.585 --> 29:51.033
And solving a grand
challenge on a fixed price

29:51.057 --> 29:54.336
is, is a challenge
in and of itself.

29:54.360 --> 29:56.271
Now, by the same token,

29:56.295 --> 30:00.876
you have to be very cost and
schedule conscience... conscious,

30:00.900 --> 30:04.012
because the sponsors of
this project have to,

30:04.036 --> 30:06.581
you know, continue to
maintain their sponsorship

30:06.605 --> 30:08.917
and believe strongly

30:08.941 --> 30:11.043
that the cost is worth
the investment.

30:15.414 --> 30:18.560
I actually got interested
in fusion as a child.

30:18.584 --> 30:22.030
Uh, my mom, when I was eight,

30:22.054 --> 30:24.599
got me what I think was
my first science book,

30:24.623 --> 30:26.568
which was about the sun.

30:26.592 --> 30:29.337
And I still remember
vividly this illustration

30:29.361 --> 30:34.209
of this hundreds of millions
of miles long coal train

30:34.233 --> 30:38.881
delivering all the coal
that equaled the energy

30:38.905 --> 30:42.484
that the sun's fusion
created in a single second.

30:42.508 --> 30:44.887
By the time I graduated,

30:44.911 --> 30:47.089
I actually didn't intend
to go into fusion

30:47.113 --> 30:52.227
because this was the high
point of the enthusiasm

30:52.251 --> 30:54.029
about the tokamak device,

30:54.053 --> 30:58.166
which is still the most
funded device in fusion.

30:58.190 --> 31:00.936
And I thought, "Well, I
guess this is solved,"

31:00.960 --> 31:03.071
and I got interested instead

31:03.095 --> 31:05.164
in astrophysics
and other things.

31:06.232 --> 31:08.643
But, um...

31:08.667 --> 31:10.946
pretty soon it
became clear, nope,

31:10.970 --> 31:12.404
it wasn't solved.

31:17.009 --> 31:20.422
The first error that was made
by the government programs

31:20.446 --> 31:22.624
back in the 1970s

31:22.648 --> 31:26.594
was to put all their eggs
in the tokamak basket.

31:26.618 --> 31:29.331
Now, 40 years later,

31:29.355 --> 31:34.102
people would have to say,
objectively we do not know

31:34.126 --> 31:39.107
which route will lead
to practical fusion,

31:39.131 --> 31:41.944
and we certainly don't
know which route will lead

31:41.968 --> 31:44.279
to the most economical fusion.

31:44.303 --> 31:49.384
What you have to do is take
a crash program approach,

31:49.408 --> 31:51.053
a broad-based approach

31:51.077 --> 31:54.189
in which, if there are 20
good ideas out there...

31:54.213 --> 31:56.624
And by good ideas,
I don't mean ideas

31:56.648 --> 31:58.726
that I think will work.

31:58.750 --> 32:02.464
I mean ideas that I
can't prove won't work.

32:02.488 --> 32:06.401
This is an important vital
question for humanity:

32:06.425 --> 32:10.238
What is an energy source that
can replace fossil fuels,

32:10.262 --> 32:14.676
that can be safe,
clean, unlimited,

32:14.700 --> 32:17.045
and more economical,

32:17.069 --> 32:19.338
cheaper than anything
we have today?

32:23.775 --> 32:25.520
I used to live on Bowen Island,

32:25.544 --> 32:26.721
so the commute was great.

32:26.745 --> 32:28.223
So I could get on my bike

32:28.247 --> 32:30.349
and it was, like, a 10
minute bike to the garage.

32:32.551 --> 32:35.530
The part will arrive, and I
would assemble all the parts,

32:35.554 --> 32:38.100
and I will actually do all
the experiments myself.

32:38.124 --> 32:40.735
There is only one guy here.
It's a one-guy show.

32:40.759 --> 32:43.195
So that was actually quite fun.
I enjoyed that.

32:44.330 --> 32:46.108
And then I would build
this machinery,

32:46.132 --> 32:49.077
and then I will fire it up, and
then I would get bad result,

32:49.101 --> 32:50.212
which is most of the
time you get that.

32:50.236 --> 32:52.614
And then I will tweak it and
adjust with a little click

32:52.638 --> 32:53.948
and some transfer somewhere.

32:53.972 --> 32:56.751
And then I started to get some
neutron coming out of this thing.

32:56.775 --> 32:59.245
So I was very excited
about my neutrons.

33:00.146 --> 33:02.290
Then, eventually, I went out

33:02.314 --> 33:04.250
and tried to raise more
money with that thing.

33:08.820 --> 33:11.199
The company got bigger
and more successful,

33:11.223 --> 33:13.992
but the fun went
downhill since then.

33:28.340 --> 33:30.585
Now, after my PhD,
sadly, I did not manage

33:30.609 --> 33:32.187
to find a job in fusion.

33:32.211 --> 33:35.290
So I got a job at a local
company doing laser printer,

33:35.314 --> 33:37.125
because I was kind
of good with lasers.

33:37.149 --> 33:39.661
Turns out that what
I was trying to do

33:39.685 --> 33:43.065
was trying to make printing so
cheap that we could cut the forest

33:43.089 --> 33:45.333
and jam you with
junk mail, you know.

33:45.357 --> 33:47.135
So that was not
very satisfactory.

33:47.159 --> 33:49.704
And I was looking at the energy
situation on the planet,

33:49.728 --> 33:51.005
and it was pretty bad.

33:51.029 --> 33:54.142
I think we're going 100 miles
an hour towards a brick wall,

33:54.166 --> 33:56.344
and nobody seems to be paying
much attention, you know.

33:56.368 --> 33:59.414
And it was actually on my birthday,
the 40-years-old birthday,

33:59.438 --> 34:02.184
and I decided I had a
terrible midlife crisis,

34:02.208 --> 34:04.319
and I say, okay,
I-I-I will change.

34:04.343 --> 34:07.455
I will not do this job
anymore, and I will do fusion.

34:07.479 --> 34:10.391
In the center of the machine,
there's a big sphere

34:10.416 --> 34:12.427
and in that sphere,
there is liquid metal.

34:12.451 --> 34:14.661
Now the liquid metal is
pumped by some pumps

34:14.686 --> 34:16.098
in those pipes over there,

34:16.121 --> 34:17.264
and it's made up to swirl.

34:17.289 --> 34:20.534
So the-the liquid is injected
near the edge like this,

34:20.559 --> 34:21.703
and it swirls around.

34:21.726 --> 34:23.804
And because it swirls around,
it appear in the center,

34:23.829 --> 34:26.474
like a centrifugal force
keep the liquid out

34:26.498 --> 34:29.210
and near the center... Up
near the center of the thing.

34:29.235 --> 34:31.746
So we fire those 14 pistons
all at the same time,

34:31.770 --> 34:33.181
and they're quite
well-synchronized.

34:33.205 --> 34:37.119
It's gonna go clonk,
clonk, clonk!

34:37.143 --> 34:39.721
And then the acoustic
waves squash the liquid,

34:39.745 --> 34:42.290
and it collapse the
vortex over the plasma.

34:42.313 --> 34:44.592
And the plasma, when you
compress it, will get hotter.

34:44.616 --> 34:47.728
And hopefully we will hit
150 million degrees C,

34:47.753 --> 34:48.896
which is the
temperature required

34:48.920 --> 34:50.732
to make the nucleus to fuse.

34:50.755 --> 34:52.400
It's piston, and it's rings.

34:52.424 --> 34:55.536
It's, uh, it's metal and pipes.
It's plumbing.

34:55.561 --> 34:58.273
Turning that into a power
plant will actually be

34:58.297 --> 35:00.475
not that complicated.

35:00.499 --> 35:02.544
I have, I have a saying
here at General Fusion

35:02.568 --> 35:05.880
I told all my engineer, "If you
can't find it at Home Depot,

35:05.904 --> 35:07.749
it doesn't go in the machine."

35:07.773 --> 35:09.617
So the tokamak and the
laser fusion have

35:09.641 --> 35:11.486
more chance of working
than what we do here,

35:11.510 --> 35:14.589
because the physics of
compressing the plasma

35:14.613 --> 35:16.358
with a magnetic field is new.

35:16.382 --> 35:18.826
However, their chance of
turning out a power plant

35:18.850 --> 35:20.895
that's cost effective is low,

35:20.919 --> 35:23.565
because their machine
is so complicated.

35:23.589 --> 35:26.234
I-I'm quite confident that
we can make this work,

35:26.258 --> 35:27.669
and I'm a little concerned

35:27.693 --> 35:30.662
that we might run out of money
before we make it work.

36:13.372 --> 36:14.782
We have everywhere problems.

36:14.806 --> 36:17.919
We have had problems
in the TF coils,

36:17.943 --> 36:19.887
uh, and it was solved.

36:19.911 --> 36:22.457
Uh, we-we could go
into the envelope

36:22.481 --> 36:24.692
with the help of Japan,
Europe, and so on.

36:24.716 --> 36:27.229
So, many things we could bring

36:27.253 --> 36:29.297
into a reasonable
envelope of schedule,

36:29.321 --> 36:31.266
but we cannot make miracles.

36:31.290 --> 36:34.302
Time lost is lost.
I cannot recover.

36:34.326 --> 36:36.438
It can only be
better from now on.

36:36.462 --> 36:38.640
The problem that I
don't understand is

36:38.664 --> 36:40.842
how are you gonna get
there 10 years from now?

36:40.866 --> 36:42.410
'Cause we heard this morning

36:42.434 --> 36:44.479
there's a problem with
the vacuum vessel,

36:44.503 --> 36:47.014
tooling issues, all
kind of things.

36:47.038 --> 36:50.552
I don't see what the plan is.

36:50.576 --> 36:53.255
But I thought you have
a much better plan,

36:53.279 --> 36:55.457
uh, when it comes to
the technologies,

36:55.481 --> 36:57.449
engineering the solutions.

36:58.350 --> 37:00.027
Whatever that is, I
mean, convince us

37:00.051 --> 37:02.530
that I think we can get
there within 10 years.

37:02.554 --> 37:04.966
This morning when
I asked the DG,

37:04.990 --> 37:08.303
what was the failure of
this whole problem was,

37:08.327 --> 37:09.871
and wasting 10 years,

37:09.895 --> 37:11.406
he said he was a manager.

37:11.430 --> 37:12.940
Right?

37:12.964 --> 37:15.301
Is there any change?
Doing anything?

38:17.429 --> 38:19.574
There's a lot depending
on ITER, right?

38:19.598 --> 38:24.612
So the whole fusion research
going on all around the world,

38:24.636 --> 38:27.949
whether it's in China,
in Europe, in the US,

38:27.973 --> 38:29.351
they all depend on ITER.

38:29.375 --> 38:31.653
So if ITER is closed down,

38:31.677 --> 38:34.356
a lot of people will not
only lose their jobs,

38:34.380 --> 38:38.626
but, um, fusion will be dead

38:38.650 --> 38:40.695
forever or at least for
a very, very long time.

38:40.719 --> 38:43.655
Nobody will ever bet on
fusion for a long time.

39:02.941 --> 39:06.745
So this is our facility where...

39:08.013 --> 39:13.351
You know, storage facility,
which is actually quite cheap.

39:14.085 --> 39:15.730
The key thing is,

39:15.754 --> 39:18.466
more money has to go
into fusion research.

39:18.490 --> 39:21.168
It has to go for
many other devices,

39:21.192 --> 39:23.562
obviously including our own.

