Even though we're a
very tiny group,

40:06.638 --> 40:09.551
science is a
collaborative effort,

40:09.575 --> 40:13.087
and we're collaborating through
the scientific literature

40:13.111 --> 40:14.913
with people all
around the world.

40:18.149 --> 40:20.161
- Hey!
- Oh, sorry.

40:20.185 --> 40:22.830
You're on camera.

40:22.854 --> 40:25.032
This is an important
member of the team.

40:25.056 --> 40:27.869
This is Tom, who's
the landlord here.

40:27.893 --> 40:29.427
Hey, guys.

40:30.762 --> 40:33.140
People ask, "How can you succeed

40:33.164 --> 40:35.810
with so few resources?"

40:35.834 --> 40:38.646
You know, are you saying you're
a thousand times smarter?

40:38.670 --> 40:39.814
No.

40:39.838 --> 40:42.040
We're saying we've
got an easier route.

40:43.709 --> 40:44.986
A plasma,

40:45.010 --> 40:48.490
which is what most of the
universe consists of,

40:48.514 --> 40:51.225
is electrically
conducting matter,

40:51.249 --> 40:54.862
matter in which the
electrons are stripped away

40:54.886 --> 40:57.832
from the atoms and can
freely move about.

40:57.856 --> 41:00.835
What we today call
the "pinch effect"

41:00.859 --> 41:06.140
forms instabilities
within the plasma,

41:06.164 --> 41:07.809
basically pinching the plasma

41:07.833 --> 41:11.245
into a lot of
filamentary structures.

41:11.269 --> 41:17.852
The conventional attitude
towards the instabilities

41:17.876 --> 41:19.053
is to suppress them.

41:19.077 --> 41:23.481
As we put it, to make the plasma
sit still like a good dog.

41:24.783 --> 41:26.994
The problem with that is
the plasma doesn't want

41:27.018 --> 41:28.062
to sit still.

41:28.086 --> 41:32.133
And trying to confine the
plasma for long enough

41:32.157 --> 41:34.802
for the fusion reactions
to take place

41:34.826 --> 41:38.139
becomes sort of like
confining a can of worms

41:38.163 --> 41:39.698
without the can.

41:40.732 --> 41:44.846
What we do is to imitate nature.

41:44.870 --> 41:50.685
In nature, on a scale of...
solar flares,

41:50.709 --> 41:53.755
quasars, entire galaxies,

41:53.779 --> 41:57.859
these filaments organize and
structure the universe.

41:57.883 --> 41:59.551
What's your trigger pressure?

42:00.351 --> 42:02.053
It's 12.36.

42:04.322 --> 42:06.625
So when the machine fires,

42:07.258 --> 42:10.037
we get a ion beam

42:10.061 --> 42:12.063
that goes down this drift tube.

42:13.632 --> 42:15.577
Once the machine fires,

42:15.601 --> 42:17.745
then it's the job of
all our instruments

42:17.769 --> 42:19.781
to find out what
actually happened.

42:19.805 --> 42:21.539
Everybody ready?

42:22.207 --> 42:24.810
Power on. Charging.

42:26.678 --> 42:29.891
So what we do in
the plasma focus

42:29.915 --> 42:32.794
is we don't try and fight
these instabilities,

42:32.818 --> 42:36.063
we try to use them to
compress the plasma

42:36.087 --> 42:37.088
and to confine them.

42:38.356 --> 42:39.825
Twenty...

42:42.360 --> 42:43.729
thirty.

42:44.362 --> 42:46.097
Set. Fire.

42:48.299 --> 42:51.212
That means the device
can be much smaller.

42:51.236 --> 42:53.915
The energy can be much
more concentrated,

42:53.939 --> 42:56.174
and that makes the
device much cheaper.

42:57.709 --> 42:59.711
Now, that was a free fire.

43:02.080 --> 43:03.114
Didn't you hear that?

43:06.985 --> 43:08.896
I just want to make sure
it's not self-firing.

43:08.920 --> 43:11.365
There was a slight
ticking noise in there

43:11.389 --> 43:12.991
I couldn't identify.

43:15.193 --> 43:16.971
The scope still set?

43:16.995 --> 43:18.596
They're dry.

43:19.865 --> 43:21.142
Power on.

43:24.035 --> 43:25.136
Charging.

43:28.974 --> 43:30.208
Ten...

43:33.144 --> 43:34.212
twenty...

43:35.413 --> 43:36.815
thirty.

43:37.448 --> 43:39.226
Set. Fire.

43:39.250 --> 43:40.828
Nope.

43:40.852 --> 43:45.399
We know of no reason why this
is physically impossible.

43:45.423 --> 43:48.870
And more, no one has told us

43:48.894 --> 43:52.406
a reason why they think this
is physically impossible.

43:52.430 --> 43:54.909
And this project is a
very public project.

43:54.933 --> 43:57.936
We've published in
peer-reviewed papers...

43:59.070 --> 44:03.751
that are among the leading
journals in our field.

44:03.775 --> 44:05.753
We've gotten a lot
of press coverage.

44:05.777 --> 44:09.290
People have a lot of opportunity
to take potshots at us.

44:09.314 --> 44:12.426
Some people say this
is a long shot,

44:12.450 --> 44:14.762
this is way out.

44:14.786 --> 44:18.900
Well, ultimately, they're just
expressing their feeling.

44:18.924 --> 44:23.695
I do say that compared
with all the other...

44:25.163 --> 44:26.774
private fusion efforts...

44:26.798 --> 44:30.068
our results at present
are the best.

44:32.103 --> 44:35.941
So, here-here... Tom just
became our latest shareholder.

44:36.775 --> 44:39.077
Yeah.

44:42.981 --> 44:44.783
Okay...

44:56.361 --> 45:00.074
It's my pleasure to
welcome all of you.

45:00.098 --> 45:01.809
I introduce myself.

45:01.833 --> 45:05.947
I'm the director-general
of the ITER organization.

45:05.971 --> 45:08.816
It is really my
honor and pleasure

45:08.840 --> 45:13.888
to address you here
today in this role.

45:13.912 --> 45:19.150
This little project as you know
is a very promising project,

45:20.886 --> 45:25.023
which now gathers
seven large parties.

45:25.857 --> 45:27.534
All of them as you know,

45:27.558 --> 45:30.171
they're representing
over 85 percent

45:30.195 --> 45:33.775
of the gross national
product in the world,

45:33.799 --> 45:36.010
and all of them are
very keen to understand

45:36.034 --> 45:40.514
how they will get their energy
supply in the long term.

45:40.538 --> 45:44.185
All of you know that there
is renewable energies,

45:44.209 --> 45:48.522
and we are very keen to see
these renewable energies

45:48.546 --> 45:50.982
to move on, to progress.

45:52.083 --> 45:55.529
But for the time
being, it is clear

45:55.553 --> 45:57.531
that it will not be able

45:57.555 --> 46:00.401
to fulfill the
expectations of the world.

46:00.425 --> 46:02.193
Oh, sorry.

46:03.895 --> 46:06.097
I will... I will say stop.

46:07.332 --> 46:08.766
Hello?

46:24.549 --> 46:26.027
Sorry.

46:26.051 --> 46:28.295
We are always
interconnected, so...

46:28.319 --> 46:33.034
As you know, renewable
energy is good for...

46:33.058 --> 46:34.969
I think we all
have great respect

46:34.993 --> 46:36.570
for what he's trying to do here,

46:36.594 --> 46:37.638
what he has to do.

46:37.662 --> 46:40.298
We are all standing behind
him, to help him to...

46:41.532 --> 46:43.510
to get the big puzzle together.

46:43.534 --> 46:45.112
It's different, right?

46:45.136 --> 46:48.182
I mean, the first two
director-generals were Japanese

46:48.206 --> 46:50.885
and certainly, um,

46:50.909 --> 46:53.354
different cultures have
different approaches

46:53.378 --> 46:55.322
to... to work with,

46:55.346 --> 46:56.924
uh, different priorities,

46:56.948 --> 46:59.894
and Mr. Bigot is a European.

46:59.918 --> 47:02.163
So for us Europeans,
it's certainly easier,

47:02.187 --> 47:04.065
right, to understand
what he wants.

47:04.089 --> 47:07.434
But if it is possible
to demonstrate

47:07.458 --> 47:10.037
and it will work for, okay,

47:10.061 --> 47:12.039
thousand and thousand of euros,

47:12.063 --> 47:13.975
I'm ready to wait for 20 years.

47:13.999 --> 47:15.433
Is not my problem.

47:19.037 --> 47:21.048
No, no, no, you know,
the sun is not obsolete

47:21.072 --> 47:22.616
even after five
billion of years.

48:00.645 --> 48:02.489
Well, I think there is something

48:02.513 --> 48:03.991
inherently difficult
about fusion.

48:04.015 --> 48:06.393
That it is, uh, an
attempt to harness

48:06.417 --> 48:09.496
some of the most difficult-
to-harness forces in nature.

48:09.520 --> 48:11.232
You have to get something

48:11.256 --> 48:14.135
at tens or hundreds of
millions of degrees Kelvin

48:14.159 --> 48:16.938
into a tight package, and
nature resists that.

48:16.962 --> 48:18.605
So tha-that is inherently hard.

48:18.629 --> 48:21.399
But on top of that, um...

48:22.567 --> 48:24.678
there seem to be
political pressures

48:24.702 --> 48:28.015
trying to blow apart
any large project.

48:28.039 --> 48:31.052
That once you have to
gather many, many people

48:31.076 --> 48:35.957
from different countries
to combine resources,

48:35.981 --> 48:38.425
especially over
decades and decades,

48:38.449 --> 48:42.629
the different political
wills, the different goals,

48:42.653 --> 48:45.032
uh, all clash with each other

48:45.056 --> 48:47.601
and eventually you wind
up with infighting,

48:47.625 --> 48:49.270
with cost overruns,

48:49.294 --> 48:52.306
and things begin to fall
apart after several years.

48:52.330 --> 48:54.976
And this is what we saw
with ITER round one,

48:55.000 --> 48:56.710
and the same thing seems
to be happening again,

48:56.734 --> 48:58.403
uh, with round two.

49:09.414 --> 49:11.592
I am often asked the question,

49:11.616 --> 49:13.627
how do you maintain
a sense of urgency

49:13.651 --> 49:16.430
on a project that takes
20 years or more?

49:16.454 --> 49:21.202
Yeah? And so the answer
is that globally...

49:21.226 --> 49:23.204
'Cause for this crowd,
the Apollo Project

49:23.228 --> 49:25.206
is what they always
think about as the...

49:25.230 --> 49:29.010
That if we think about
how short for most of us

49:29.034 --> 49:31.145
20 years ago really seems and
all that has happened...

49:31.169 --> 49:34.181
The Secretary of Energy
was asked specifically

49:34.205 --> 49:37.218
to make a recommendation by
the second of May this year

49:37.242 --> 49:39.386
on that topic, a
progress report on ITER,

49:39.410 --> 49:41.788
and should the US stay
in or should they not.

49:41.812 --> 49:45.392
Yeah, I think that
it's quite clear

49:45.416 --> 49:48.262
that, uh, things are moving
in a positive direction,

49:48.286 --> 49:51.732
but we were digging out of
a fairly significant hole,

49:51.756 --> 49:54.468
and so progress was
really necessary.

49:54.492 --> 49:57.304
It's up to the American
Congress to make the decision,

49:57.328 --> 50:00.598
you know, if the
project will deliver.

50:11.509 --> 50:14.588
Sub-Committee on Energy
will come to order.

50:14.612 --> 50:18.059
And we wanna welcome you to
today's hearing entitled,

50:18.083 --> 50:21.128
"An Overview of Fusion
Energy Science."

50:21.152 --> 50:23.364
Is it ee-ter or eye-ter?

50:23.388 --> 50:25.299
- Ee-ter.
- Ee-ter. Hmm. Okay.

50:25.323 --> 50:27.801
Tokamak. I keep wanting
to say "Tomahawk,"

50:27.825 --> 50:29.403
and I know that's...

50:29.427 --> 50:30.771
that's not right.

50:30.795 --> 50:34.441
With the complexity of a multi-national
collaboration like ITER,

50:34.465 --> 50:38.579
this project has faced
more challenges than most.

50:38.603 --> 50:41.082
Fortunately, today, we have
the opportunity to hear

50:41.106 --> 50:43.350
from the director-general of
the ITER project directly,

50:43.374 --> 50:46.353
Dr. Bernard... Is it Bee-go?

50:46.377 --> 50:49.256
Uh, I do believe if we have
the proper management,

50:49.280 --> 50:51.825
we will be able to
deliver on time.

50:51.849 --> 50:53.694
We have spent how much money

50:53.718 --> 50:55.496
over the last ten years,
the United States?

50:55.520 --> 50:57.698
When the US signed
up for the project,

50:57.722 --> 50:59.366
you know, the
representation was made

50:59.390 --> 51:01.202
that this project
was ready to go

51:01.226 --> 51:02.769
to an extent that,
in retrospect,

51:02.793 --> 51:03.937
probably wasn't the case.

51:03.961 --> 51:08.575
When you think about what we
spent on imported oil alone...

51:08.599 --> 51:12.313
I just want to understand
the dimensions of the cliff

51:12.337 --> 51:14.815
that we're playing near when we
talk about the US pulling out.

51:14.839 --> 51:19.186
If you're gonna have to lay
odds on, on all the engineering

51:19.210 --> 51:21.488
and all these things
coming together,

51:21.512 --> 51:24.225
uh... what are your odds?

51:24.249 --> 51:27.728
I do believe this project
could be so beneficial

51:27.752 --> 51:30.764
to the world, that
it is really worth

51:30.788 --> 51:32.733
to try and to demonstrate.

51:32.757 --> 51:34.601
- And again...
- Let me mention this.

51:34.625 --> 51:38.172
There are a lot of wonderful
things we can do in this world.

51:38.196 --> 51:40.541
- I know.
- Wonderful things.

51:40.565 --> 51:41.875
- And...
- Including ITER.

51:41.899 --> 51:44.611
Yeah, um, okay. And ITER
may be one of them,

51:44.635 --> 51:48.615
but what we do is we judge
each one based on the cost

51:48.639 --> 51:51.618
and the chances of success.

51:51.642 --> 51:55.256
Because, in theory, it's such
a beautiful and simple idea.

51:55.280 --> 51:57.391
Yet, throughout,
people have found

51:57.415 --> 52:00.627
as soon as they get
around the next corner,

52:00.651 --> 52:02.763
there is yet another hurdle.

52:02.787 --> 52:05.699
Um, and nature seems
to have this way

52:05.723 --> 52:07.668
of throwing up, um,

52:07.692 --> 52:11.238
blockade after blockade
after blockade that makes

52:11.262 --> 52:14.632
scientists' optimism,
uh, look naive.

52:16.567 --> 52:19.446
My favorite fusion conman,

52:19.470 --> 52:22.440
uh, was Richter from Argentina.

52:25.776 --> 52:28.489
He was a German or
Austrian expat...

52:28.513 --> 52:30.924
We actually know very
little about him...

52:30.948 --> 52:33.960
Who moved to Argentina

52:33.984 --> 52:36.330
and managed to
convince Juan Peron

52:36.354 --> 52:37.831
that he had figured out a method

52:37.855 --> 52:40.801
of, uh, harnessing the sun

52:40.825 --> 52:42.427
and called it thermotron.

52:43.728 --> 52:46.631
And so they built this
secret lab on an island.

52:47.565 --> 52:52.313
And this crazy expat
was running around

52:52.337 --> 52:53.947
pouring gunpowder
in experiments,

52:53.971 --> 52:55.849
blowing doors off his lab,

52:55.873 --> 52:58.319
writing fusion on ticker
tapes everywhere,

52:58.343 --> 53:01.555
convincing everyone for a
matter of months and years

53:01.579 --> 53:04.782
that he has solved the
world's energy problems.

53:17.928 --> 53:20.807
Until he was finally found out
as a fraud and wound up in jail.

53:25.336 --> 53:28.014
One of the things that's
interesting about his story

53:28.038 --> 53:31.485
is that the physicists

53:31.509 --> 53:34.788
who first thought
about magnetic fusion

53:34.812 --> 53:35.989
were inspired by his story.

53:36.013 --> 53:40.827
They saw a front page
New York Times claim

53:40.851 --> 53:43.897
about fusion energy
in Argentina,

53:43.921 --> 53:45.599
and the scientists
here were thinking,

53:45.623 --> 53:47.358
how could that be done?

53:55.633 --> 53:58.345
My wife and I were planning
to leave for Aspen,

53:58.369 --> 53:59.646
and my father, he said,

53:59.670 --> 54:02.516
"Well, I understand the
Argentines have, uh,

54:02.540 --> 54:05.386
have gotten ahead of you
in the fusion program."

54:05.410 --> 54:08.522
He'd seen the New
York Times article

54:08.546 --> 54:12.326
that a fellow named Richter
had released fusion

54:12.350 --> 54:14.027
in a controlled
manner in Argentina,

54:14.051 --> 54:16.430
and Peron made quite
a thing of it.

54:16.454 --> 54:17.964
I read the New York
Times article.

54:17.988 --> 54:21.392
Then we got on a
train down to Aspen.

54:32.002 --> 54:35.682
It was during the intervals out
there, when we weren't skiing,

54:35.706 --> 54:37.484
I was thinking about this.

54:37.508 --> 54:41.388
How would one do it if
one were trying to?

54:41.412 --> 54:44.491
I worked out some of
the general ideas

54:44.515 --> 54:48.786
that I later developed
into the stellarator.

54:50.388 --> 54:53.033
So Spitzer came up
with this cool device

54:53.057 --> 54:54.568
called the stellarator.

54:54.592 --> 54:57.070
Stellarators are a
complicated machine,

54:57.094 --> 54:59.740
and they have worse
confinement in general.

54:59.764 --> 55:02.743
But there's no such thing as
disruption in a stellarator.

55:02.767 --> 55:05.746
And so stellarators
for the past decade

55:05.770 --> 55:07.548
have just been more
and more complicated.

55:07.572 --> 55:10.016
They look like squid fighting
each other at this point.

55:10.040 --> 55:13.820
You can specify what magnetic
field configuration you want.

55:13.844 --> 55:16.823
So then you give the computer
the job of iterating

55:16.847 --> 55:18.525
through a bunch of
possible different coils

55:18.549 --> 55:21.362
until it gets to the right
magnetic field configuration.

55:21.386 --> 55:23.830
And you end up with
something weird, like this.

55:23.854 --> 55:25.198
It's cool, right?

55:25.222 --> 55:28.426
All right, any other questions
before we move on to the tokamak?

55:29.494 --> 55:30.895
Okay, let's bust a move.

55:53.484 --> 55:56.029
So W7-X is a really
cool experiment.

55:56.053 --> 55:58.031
It's a stellarator which has

55:58.055 --> 55:59.633
a lot of advantages
over a tokamak.

55:59.657 --> 56:01.668
The biggest advantage is
that it can just run.

56:01.692 --> 56:05.739
It just... You know,
for hours hopefully.

56:05.763 --> 56:08.609
And once you can do that, you
can build a power plant.

56:08.633 --> 56:11.745
Um, and so tokamaks right
now have a problem

56:11.769 --> 56:14.080
where they just, they
can't run continuously,

56:14.104 --> 56:16.049
but this experiment is
designed to show that

56:16.073 --> 56:17.183
it can be done continuously

56:17.207 --> 56:20.887
at parameters that are good
enough for fusion, so...

56:20.911 --> 56:23.189
I came here, and I came to
know about stellarators

56:23.213 --> 56:25.158
and somewhere along
the line, I switched

56:25.182 --> 56:28.795
from believing in tokamaks
to more in stellarators,

56:28.819 --> 56:30.096
and I thought, yeah,

56:30.120 --> 56:31.989
maybe this is the future
of energy and fusion.

56:35.092 --> 56:38.171
This project would not
have been possible

56:38.195 --> 56:39.906
without the reunion of Germany.

56:39.930 --> 56:44.044
It is co-financed by
Europe to a big extent.

56:44.068 --> 56:47.213
But still the project
team is in our hands.

56:47.237 --> 56:50.517
We had to take care that
we have young people

56:50.541 --> 56:53.086
being able to do physics
now with the new machine

56:53.110 --> 56:56.590
and really to make this a team.

56:56.614 --> 57:01.595
Wendelstein is a highly
optimized stellerator device,

57:01.619 --> 57:02.963
three-dimensional design.

57:02.987 --> 57:05.065
It goes back about 20 years.

57:05.089 --> 57:09.002
And, um, to build this, to get
the support to build this,

57:09.026 --> 57:12.673
they had to build it in the
then-reuniting Germany.

57:12.697 --> 57:14.708
It's a crucial
part of the story.

57:14.732 --> 57:16.977
So they started a
completely new institute

57:17.001 --> 57:18.545
from nothing up here.

57:18.569 --> 57:22.849
And they had to go into building something
that had never been built before.

57:22.873 --> 57:27.187
Now, unsurprisingly, it
ended up being more complex

57:27.211 --> 57:29.980
and expensive and difficult
than they planned.

59:56.994 --> 59:59.372
Big emotion. Big
emotion, you know.

59:59.396 --> 01:00:01.908
I do believe it's
really a landmark

01:00:01.932 --> 01:00:06.747
in the history of fusion to
see with these stellarators

01:00:06.771 --> 01:00:08.381
it works right away.

01:00:08.405 --> 01:00:09.716
Very good.

01:00:09.740 --> 01:00:11.918
She's a really great scientist,

01:00:11.942 --> 01:00:15.355
and she know how to organize
the work of this people

01:00:15.379 --> 01:00:17.423
to give good priorities,

01:00:17.447 --> 01:00:19.793
and I really believe she deserve

01:00:19.817 --> 01:00:21.962
full recognition for
her achievement.

01:00:35.700 --> 01:00:37.277
Well, this fusion business

01:00:37.301 --> 01:00:39.780
has been going a little slower
than we were all hoping

01:00:39.804 --> 01:00:41.114
when we started this company.

01:00:41.138 --> 01:00:42.282
We started with great gusto,

01:00:42.306 --> 01:00:44.317
"Yeah, we're gonna
whisk that up."

01:00:44.341 --> 01:00:46.419
And then we ran
into difficulties,

01:00:46.443 --> 01:00:49.055
so it's a little longer
than what we wanted.

01:00:49.079 --> 01:00:51.291
So it's a little bit
more challenging.

01:00:51.315 --> 01:00:55.095
But we-we're still optimistic
that we're doing good progress.

01:00:55.119 --> 01:00:56.763
It's going a little
slower than I'd like,

01:00:56.787 --> 01:00:58.298
but it's-it's advancing forward.

01:00:58.322 --> 01:00:59.499
So we're not kind of stopped.

01:00:59.523 --> 01:01:03.369
So mood is okay, but now we're,
we're kind of gearing up

01:01:03.393 --> 01:01:07.373
for a bit more of a long run
than a, than a quick success.

01:01:07.397 --> 01:01:09.209
We're certainly not
the startup anymore,

01:01:09.233 --> 01:01:13.413
like we used to be a real
scruffy little startup,

01:01:13.437 --> 01:01:15.882
but now we're getting
more people,

01:01:15.906 --> 01:01:18.484
it's a bigger shop, and
been here for a few years.

01:01:18.508 --> 01:01:20.144
We have shown some result.

01:01:21.145 --> 01:01:23.389
This is 1,500 microseconds.

01:01:23.413 --> 01:01:24.958
The compression time is only

01:01:24.982 --> 01:01:27.894
180 microseconds, a
little time here.

01:01:27.918 --> 01:01:29.329
So the magnetic field is
going up and up and up.

01:01:29.353 --> 01:01:33.066
This is good. This is what we want
when you compress magnetic field.

01:01:33.090 --> 01:01:35.468
But then again you see
all those oscillations,

01:01:35.492 --> 01:01:38.171
both on the outside sensor
and the inside sensor

01:01:38.195 --> 01:01:40.073
and then the plasma crash,

01:01:40.097 --> 01:01:41.141
like it-it dies here.

01:01:41.165 --> 01:01:43.944
What we want it to do is
to go up, up, up, up, up,

01:01:43.968 --> 01:01:45.979
probably to about
this height here.

01:01:52.777 --> 01:01:56.823
So, we're clamping
it now, um, Claude,

01:01:56.847 --> 01:01:59.259
so stop flowing. Stop flowing!

01:01:59.283 --> 01:02:01.886
- Okay!
- Okay.

01:02:03.287 --> 01:02:04.865
This is always a
stressful event,

01:02:04.889 --> 01:02:06.332
because if we let air
into the chamber,

01:02:06.356 --> 01:02:09.069
it's filled with moisture, and it
will ruin the quality of our vacuum.

01:02:09.093 --> 01:02:10.895
It will take weeks and
weeks to recover.

01:02:13.497 --> 01:02:14.999
Ooh, gosh.

01:02:23.507 --> 01:02:26.286
All right, go on, cut
the flow in... now.

01:02:26.310 --> 01:02:28.254
Cut it now.

01:02:28.278 --> 01:02:30.123
Very good. Thanks.

01:02:30.147 --> 01:02:30.991
We did it.

01:02:31.015 --> 01:02:32.993
Five years ago when
we were staring up

01:02:33.017 --> 01:02:34.460
and building our first machines,

01:02:34.484 --> 01:02:36.029
we were having things
blow up every day.

01:02:36.053 --> 01:02:38.398
It was... People were scared.

01:02:38.422 --> 01:02:40.224
The siren really made
people frightened.

01:02:44.261 --> 01:02:46.206
There's no point building
the wrong thing though.

01:02:46.230 --> 01:02:49.109
I got it. Yeah, absolutely.
I know. I know.

01:02:49.133 --> 01:02:51.878
But the flip side of that
is that that can go on

01:02:51.902 --> 01:02:53.914
- for a while, right?
- Mm-hmm.

